controlnet training resize inputs to multiple of 8 (#3135)

controlnet training center crop input images to multiple of 8

The pipeline code resizes inputs to multiples of 8.
Not doing this resizing in the training script is causing
the encoded image to have different height/width dimensions
than the encoded conditioning image (which uses a separate
encoder that's part of the controlnet model).

We resize and center crop the inputs to make sure they're the
same size (as well as all other images in the batch). We also
check that the initial resolution is a multiple of 8.

1.Reimplement the following:

  - invokeai-model-install
  - invokeai-merge
  - invokeai-ti

  To avoid breaking the original modeal manager, the udpated tools
  have been renamed invokeai-model-install2 and invokeai-merge2. The
  textual inversion training script should continue to work with
  existing installations. The "starter" models now live in
  `invokeai/configs/INITIAL_MODELS2.yaml`.

  When the full model manager 2 is in place and working, I'll rename
  these files and commands.

2. Add the `merge` route to the web API. This will merge two or three models,
   resulting a new one.

   - Note that because the model installer selectively installs the `fp16` variant
     of models (rather than both 16- and 32-bit versions as previous),
     the diffusers merge script will choke on any huggingface diffuserse models
     that were downloaded with the new installer. Previously-downloaded models
     should continue to merge correctly. I have a PR
     upstream https://github.com/huggingface/diffusers/pull/6670 to fix
     this.

3. (more important!)
  During implementation of the CLI tools, found and fixed a number of small
  runtime bugs in the model_manager2 implementation:

  - During model database migration, if a registered models file was
    not found on disk, the migration would be aborted. Now the
    offending model is skipped with a log warning.

  - Caught and fixed a condition in which the installer would download the
    entire diffusers repo when the user provided a single `.safetensors`
    file URL.

  - Caught and fixed a condition in which the installer would raise an
    exception and stop the app when a request for an unknown model's metadata
    was passed to Civitai. Now an error is logged and the installer continues.

  - Replaced the LoWRA starter LoRA with FlatColor. The former has been removed
    from Civitai.

* fix ruff issue

fixes to env parsing, textual inversion & help text

- Make environment variable settings case InSenSiTive:
  INVOKEAI_MAX_LOADED_MODELS and InvokeAI_Max_Loaded_Models
  environment variables will both set `max_loaded_models`

- Updated realesrgan to use new config system.

- Updated textual_inversion_training to use new config system.

- Discovered a race condition when InvokeAIAppConfig is created
  at module load time, which makes it impossible to customize
  or replace the help message produced with --help on the command
  line. To fix this, moved all instances of get_invokeai_config()
  from module load time to object initialization time. Makes code
  cleaner, too.

- Added `--from_file` argument to `invokeai-node-cli` and changed
  github action to match. CI tests will hopefully work now.

This test currently fails in main. When switching from DEIS to UniPC,
solver_type is "logrho" (the default value from DEIS), which gets
translated to "bh1" by UniPC. This is different to the default value for
UniPC: "bh2". This is where the translation happens: https://github.com/huggingface/diffusers/blob/36d22d0709dc19776e3016fb3392d0f5578b0ab2/src/diffusers/schedulers/scheduling_unipc_multistep.py#L171

* UniPC: use same default for solver_type

Fixes a bug when switching from UniPC from another scheduler (i.e.,
DEIS) that uses a different solver type. The solver is now the same as
if we had instantiated the scheduler directly.

Stable Diffusion Latent Upscaler (#2059)

* Modify UNet2DConditionModel

- allow skipping mid_block

- adding a norm_group_size argument so that we can set the `num_groups` for group norm using `num_channels//norm_group_size`

- allow user to set dimension for the timestep embedding (`time_embed_dim`)

- the kernel_size for `conv_in` and `conv_out` is now configurable

- add random fourier feature layer (`GaussianFourierProjection`) for `time_proj`

- allow user to add the time and class embeddings before passing through the projection layer together - `time_embedding(t_emb + class_label))`

- added 2 arguments `attn1_types` and `attn2_types`

  * currently we have argument `only_cross_attention`: when it's set to `True`, we will have a to the
`BasicTransformerBlock` block with 2 cross-attention , otherwise we
get a self-attention followed by a cross-attention; in k-upscaler, we need to have blocks that include just one cross-attention, or self-attention -> cross-attention;
so I added `attn1_types` and `attn2_types` to the unet's argument list to allow user specify the attention types for the 2 positions in each block;  note that I stil kept
the `only_cross_attention` argument for unet for easy configuration, but it will be converted to `attn1_type` and `attn2_type` when passing down to the down blocks

- the position of downsample layer and upsample layer is now configurable

- in k-upscaler unet, there is only one skip connection per each up/down block (instead of each layer in stable diffusion unet), added `skip_freq = "block"` to support
this use case

- if user passes attention_mask to unet, it will prepare the mask and pass a flag to cross attention processer to skip the `prepare_attention_mask` step
inside cross attention block

add up/down blocks for k-upscaler

modify CrossAttention class

- make the `dropout` layer in `to_out` optional

- `use_conv_proj` - use conv instead of linear for all projection layers (i.e. `to_q`, `to_k`, `to_v`, `to_out`) whenever possible. note that when it's used to do cross
attention, to_k, to_v has to be linear because the `encoder_hidden_states` is not 2d

- `cross_attention_norm` - add an optional layernorm on encoder_hidden_states

- `attention_dropout`: add an optional dropout on attention score

adapt BasicTransformerBlock

- add an ada groupnorm layer  to conditioning attention input with timestep embedding

- allow skipping the FeedForward layer in between the attentions

- replaced the only_cross_attention argument with attn1_type and attn2_type for more flexible configuration

update timestep embedding: add new act_fn  gelu and an optional act_2

modified ResnetBlock2D

- refactored with AdaGroupNorm class (the timestep scale shift normalization)

- add `mid_channel` argument - allow the first conv to have a different output dimension from the second conv

- add option to use input AdaGroupNorm on the input instead of groupnorm

- add options to add a dropout layer after each conv

- allow user to set the bias in conv_shortcut (needed for k-upscaler)

- add gelu

adding conversion script for k-upscaler unet

feat(build): separate MODEL_REVISION, MODEL_PRECISION, HF_MODEL_ID

The above already worked for runtime downloads, but can now be used
as build-args to download the image at build time and include in your
image.

SOME VERY IMPORTANT NOTES:

1) MODEL_REVISION no longer defaults to MODEL_PRECISION, you need to
specify it separately (however, still defaults to "fp16" in Dockerfile).
You'll get a warning if you specify MODEL_PRECISION without _REVISION,
to help in the most common case of the old behaviour.

2) build-arg PRECISION still works but has been deprecated for
MODEL_PRECISION (which was already the call-arg name).

3) normalized_model_id uses MODEL_REVISION, so for the early birds
already using the "cloud cache" on S3, your filenames might no
longer match in some cases.

It defaults to balanced, which is standard uniform time step sampling. updated kubeflow pipeline and k8s app with daal4py 2024.0 api and updated stable diffusion documentation (#13)

* updated kubeflow pipeline and k8s app with daal4py 2024.0 api and updated stable diffusion documentation

* updated transformers from 4.30.0 to 4.36.0

* updated README.md

combines message, image, error and tqdm handler into single call

emits message and uses signal + handlers to sort what message was posted

modifications to schedulers

adds additional schedulers
fixes scheduler loading and switching for ckpt and safetensors
Moves more functions to mixin files for easier to read code
rearranged the file and add upscaler feature
Fixed a bug in the text encoder mutation and the attention mask.
Support mutation and attention mask for text embedding.
Hack to follow up a recent diffusers change in applying textual inversion

Introduce vicinity model and v-t model for clip text deprojector
* The all clip text deprojector models are moved to an independent module.
* Modify the training code and the training data loading code.
Move ConstructInput to the derived class.

Introduce `fuse` parameter to CLIPtextDeprojector.

Fuse is a ratio of merging individual prev_output and average prev_output.
Use only individual prev_output if fuse = 0.0.
Use only average prev_output if fuse = 1.0.
Fix a bug in the ensemble model.

Supported a new architecture to apply an MLP to input
Detail is explained in https://note.com/tomo161382/n/nc5aaeee4dbf4
Also moved some parameters to CLIPTextDeprojectorconfig.

Make the ensemble model loadable from a saved config
* Introduced CLIPTextDeprojectorConfig derived from CLIPTextConfig.

Introduced ensemble models for CLIPTextDeprojector
* Some models are experimental or deprecated and will be removed later.

Updated CLIPTextDeprojector
* Changed the control parameters from instance variables to function arguments
  * Refactored the logic to construct the input to the model into ConstructInput()
* Implement experimental temporal features to change the last hidden state after EOS in TextModel
* Modified experimental ImageEncoding to use `base_image_emb`
* Implemented the `diff_only` mode in PooledEncoding.

Add two experimental encodings (ImageEncoding and PooledEncoding)

Also a few minor fixes.

Introduce CLIPTextDeprojector

CLIPTextDeprojector is to "deproject" the projected text embedding of the CLIP text model to the last hidden state.
The model data is found in https://huggingface.co/nanashi161382/clip-text-deprojector.

This also
* disabled the NSFW filter because it isn't used at all,
* changed how the tokenizer overflow is treated.

Don't use alpha in the model data
* alpha in the model data is only for training and not for inference.

Allow different alphas in LoRA
* two different alphas for the text encoder and the unet.

How to use:

pipe = LayeredDiffusionPipeline().ConnectCkpt(
    "Anything_v3",
    checkpoint_path="anything-v3-fp32-pruned.safetensors",
    lora=LoRA().Add(
        "Japanese-doll-likeness.safetensors",
        alpha=0.7,
        text_encoder_alpha=1.0,
    ),
)

Changed API for LoRA
The new API allows to
* Apply multiple LoRA
* Overwrite alpha
* Skip updating text encoder and/or unet

Fully support LoRA
* Rewrite LoraSideloader
* Now it fully supports the 1111 format.
* It doesn't support the diffusers format anymore.

Partially support LoRA
* Support UNet LoRA
* Support conversion from 1111 LoRA format to diffusers LoRA format
* Not all 1111 Lora model parameters are supported by diffusers.
Rename scale to post_scale in ControlNet

Fix a bug in GradationCanny()
* Added image conversion between Pillow and CV2.
Added GradationCanny() as a helper function for Canny ControlNet.

Add support for Textual Inversion

* Add support for Textual Inversion
* Add pre-scale and detector for ControlNet

How to use Textual Inversion.

embeddings = TextualInversion().Add(
    "EasyNegative",
    "/path/to/embeddings/EasyNegative.safetensors")
pipe = LayeredDiffusionPipeline().ConnectCkpt(
    model_name, ckpt_file, embeddings=embeddings)

Improved memory management

* Add Dispose() to offload model data from GPU memory and destruct the pipeline
* Fixed some bugs

Support ControlNet

* Add support for ControlNet
* Add an option to flip the mask image
* Support .ckpt and .safetensors files as a VAE model file
* Changed extract_ema's default value to True
* Add support for textual_inversion embeddings but need to wait for the next diffusers release

Here is how to use ControlNet from this pipeline.

ctn_canny = ControlNetModel.from_pretrained("lllyasviel/sd-controlnet-canny")
image = pipe(
  num_steps=30,
  size=(512, 512),
  iterate=Layer(
    prompt="ocean",
  ),
  controlnet=ControlNet().Add(ctb_canny, "canny.png", 0.7),
)

Allow the pt format for sideloaded VAE

Now vae_path for ConnectCkpt() accepts the pt format as well as the diffusers format.

Changed use_xformers default value to True

I really changed the default value of use_xformers now.

Allow loading different VAE with SD ckpt

Added support to load different VAE to ConnectCkpt().
However, the VAE data format has to be the diffusers format (bin file) rather than the SD-webui format (pt file).

Also, this changed the default value of `use_xformers` to True because I confirmed it now works without any special settings.

Here is how it is used.
----
model_name = "author/project/model_name"  # This is required for historical reason. Empty string is OK.
ckpt_file = "/path/to/model_name.ckpt" # or "/path/to/model_name.safetensors"
vae_path = "/path/to/vae/directory" # It should contain "config.json" and "diffusion_pytorch_model.bin"

pipe = LayeredDiffusionPipeline().ConnectCkpt(model_name, ckpt_file, vae_path)

Support Stable Diffusion ckpt model format

Added a function ConnectCkpt() to LayeredDiffusionPipeline to load Stable Diffusion's model format (ckpt and safetensors).

Sample usage in Google Colab:

!wget https://huggingface.co/Linaqruf/anything-v3.0/resolve/main/anything-v3-fp32-pruned.safetensors \
  -O /content/drive/MyDrive/sd_models/anything-v3/anything-v3-fp32-pruned.safetensors

dataset = "Linaqruf/anything-v3.0"
ckpt_file = "/content/drive/MyDrive/sd_models/anything-v3/anything-v3-fp32-pruned.safetensors"
pipe = LayeredDiffusionPipeline().ConnectCkpt(dataset, ckpt_file)

introduce negative_scale

replace negative_sot_scale with negative_scale so as to set both the sot scale and the rest scale for negative prompts.

Major change on text encodings

The change is based on the new article, https://github.com/nanashi161382/unstable_diffusion/wiki/Is-the-Start-Of-Text-token-meaningful-for-Stable-Diffusion-image-generation%3F

Here is a list of changes
- null_prompt and NullPrompt are removed
- negative_sot_scale is introduced and the default value is set to 0.8
- ZeroEmbedding and UnitEmbedding are introduced
- ScaledEncoding takes two scale factors as tuple for SOT and the rest
Fix BackGroundLayer's scale for SPLayer again.

Refactor DecomposedResidual

This doesn't change the interface but refactor DecomposedResidual class.
This changes the behavior of layer merge process slightly, but shouldn't affect very much in most cases.

Disable weight normalization by default

* Disable weight normalization in ShiftEncoding by default.
* Change the weight normalization behavior to normalizing all the token weights instead of only the prompt token weights.
* Clean up the old buggy weight normalization.

Cleaned up Layers API

Major API clean-up/modification of Layers API.
Here are a list of changes.
* Background Layer doesn't use a hidden prompt anymore.
* `is_zero_sum` argument is replaced by `to_add` argument.
* With use_decomposed_rmm=True, all Layers are zero-sum.
* `for_negative` of SPLayer constructor is removed. `negative_prompt` is allowed instead.

NullPrompt, ConstEncoding, ScaledEncoding, etc

This commit made a fairly big change to the features and the default behaviors.
First, there are two new Encodings.
- ConstEncoding  -- encoding that generates text embedding whose elements are all the same value
- ScaledEncoding  -- encoding that multiplies the output of a nested encoding by a given factor

Then, the pipeline now allows to change the default text embedding via the `null_prompt` argument, and changed ConstEncoding(0.0) as default, which was previously an empty string ("").
For the difference between an empty string and ConstEncoding(0.0), see https://note.com/tomo161382/n/n318648aa4ab7.
You can also use a special keyword `NullPrompt` to specify the `null_prompt` embedding explicitly in Layer prompts.

Third, I changed the `Layer` class from a normal layer to a zero-sum layer by default.
I will eventually remove the non-zero-sum option from `Layer`.

Fourth, you can use a zero and negative weight in ShiftEncoding.

Fifth, by default, weights in ShiftEncoding are normalized to 1.0 before applying.

Fixed a bug when inserting an initializer

It sometimes inserted a redundant Randomly() initializer before this commit.

SPLayer, ZeroSum Layer, Variable CFG, RangeMap

The biggest framework changes of this commit are
- decomposed RMM
- RangeMap

The deomposed RMM is a variant of RMM that does CFG after processing all the layers instead of doing at the end of each layer.
This enables supporting SPLayer (Single-Prompt Layer) which contains only either prompt or negative_prompt.
See https://note.com/tomo161382/n/n15c70adfe6a0 for details.

RangeMap is a new syntax that supports all of image strength, layer strength, cfg scale, prompt and negative prompt in a uniformed way.
Previously the generalized strength has the following format.
* strength = 0.8
* strength = strg(0.6, until=0.8)
* strength = [strg(0.4, until=0.8), strg(0.6, until=0.7)]
And prompt and negative_prompt has the following format.
* prompt = "1girl"
* prompt = (0.2, "1girl")
* prompt = [(0.0, "1girl"), (0.3, "1girl, 1boy")]
Cfg_scale didn't have a way to change the value in the image processing.
Now they are written in a uniformed way using RangeMap as follows.
* strength = 0.8
* strength = using(0.6, until=0.8)
* strength = using(0.4, until=0.8).then(0.6, until=0.7)
* prompt = "1girl"
* prompt = using("1girl", after=0.2)
* prompt = using("1girl", until=0.3).then("1girl, 1boy")
* cfg_scale = 4.0
* cfg_scale = using(16.0, after=0.8)

ZeroSum Layer doesn't fall into either of the two above.
It is to make a layer additive rather than multiplicative as a normal layer is.
See https://note.com/tomo161382/n/n1128983166e9 for details.

Add support for transparent PNGs

* Treat the alpha channel as a mask image
* Randomly initialize the transparent part of the input image
* Allow overlaying multiple input images with masks

Introduced generalized strength

Generalized strength is an extension of strength used for image to image and inpainting.
It is now applied to both initializers (such as input images) and iteration layers.
It defined as a list of pairs of the remaining timestep ratio and the level of application.
If levels are omitted, then they are assumed linearly.
Here are examples.
 * strength = None  => interpreted as 1.0. Level is automatically calculated.
 * strength = 0.9
 * strength = strg(0.9, level=0.5)  => `strg` is short for `Strength`.
 * strength = [0.9, 0.7]
 * strength = [strg(0.9, level=0.8), strg(0.7, level=0.4)]

This commit also allows a list of initializers for the `initilize` parameter, and each initializer contains a mask and a strength.
The `layers` parameter is also renames as `iterate`.

Here is an example of the new pipeline.

```
pipe(
    initialize=ByImage(
        image="input.png",
        strength=[0.9, 0.5],
    ),
    iterate=[
        Layer(
            prompt= "grass field, cherry tree, blue sky",
            negative_prompt= "dog",
            strength=strg(0.7, level=0.6),
        ),
        Layer(
            prompt= "white persian cat",
            negative_prompt= "",
            mask_by="mask.png",
            strength=strg(0.7, level=0.6),
        ),
    ],
    num_steps=30,
    size=(512, 512),
)
```

Moved fontname to global variable

Changed 'fontname' in ConcatImages() to a global variable 'FONTNAME' so as to modify the font from outside of the module.

Reduce memory usage during image decoding

The pipeline causes OOM if the image size is big (such as 768 x 512).
It happens during image decoding by the VAE.
This commit changed the decoding process from a single batch to a sequential method.

This also made it produce a summary image of the RMM images instead of returning all individual images.

Refactoring. Introduced MergeMethod classes.

Refactored the code that was introduced by the previous commit.
MLL is renamed to RMM (Residual Merge Method).
And Layer's `is_additional` is renamed to `is_distinct`.

LMM (Latent Merge Method) is the conventional way to merge layers with latents.
RMM (Residual Merge Method) is the new way to merge layers with residuals and it enables distinct layers.
Now RMM is the default merge method.

For an example of RMM and distinct layers, see https://twitter.com/tomo161382/status/1605201010733219842

Introduce MLL generation

MLL (multi-level layer) is a tentative name of a new pipeline implementation (that I came up with in just a few seconds).
I will rename it later.

It synthesizes layers with residuals rather than with latents.
It allows to mark part of layers as "additional" so that additional layers don't affect each other.
Example: https://twitter.com/tomo161382/status/1604992539731595264

The code is very rough and messy. I must refactor and clean it up later.

Add exclude_by to Layer

Example output: https://twitter.com/tomo161382/status/1604414960817143808

Example code:
```
          Layer(
              prompt= "white cat is sittng",
              negative_prompt= "black dog",
              mask_by="mask_right.png",
              exclude_by="mask_left.png",
          )
```

Get rid of prompt dictionary

Now prompts are defined directly in each layer.

Example:
```
pipe(
    num_steps=30,
    initialize=Randomly(),
    size=image_size,
    layers=Layer(
        prompt="black dog",
        negative_prompt="white cat",
        cfg_scale=7.5,
    ),
)
```

Allow non list as layers

a quick fix to the previous commit.

Simplified API related to layers

The API related to layers is too complicated to understand intuitively.
This change simplify the API by the following change.
* Delete `bg_strength`
* Pipeline no longer accepts `prompt_name`, `negative_prompt_name`, and `cfg_scale` as direct parameters.
* The default value of Layer's `mask_by` is set to 1.0 (= masking everything)
* Layer has a new parameter `skip_until`.
* Deleted `ForImg2Img` and `ForInpaint`.

Normal pipeline call is as follows.
```
pipe(
    num_steps=30,
    prompts = {
        "prompt": "black dog",
        "negative": "white cat",
    },
    initialize=Randomly(),
    size=image_size,
    layers=Layer(
        prompt_name="prompt",
        negative_prompt_name="negative",
        cfg_scale=7.5,
    ),
)
```

Image to image is like
```
pipe(
    num_steps=30,
    prompts = {
        "prompt": "black dog",
        "negative": "white cat",
    },
    initialize=ByImage(
        image="input.png",
    ),
    size=image_size,
    layers=Layer(
        prompt_name="prompt",
        negative_prompt_name="negative",
        cfg_scale=7.5,
    ),
)
```

Inpaint is as
```
pipe(
    num_steps=30,
    prompts = {
        "prompt": "black dog",
        "negative": "white cat",
    },
    initialize=ByImage(
        image="input.png",
    ),
    size=image_size,
    layers=Layer(
        prompt_name="prompt",
        negative_prompt_name="negative",
        cfg_scale=7.5,
        mask_by="mask.png",
    ),
)
```

Added ForImg2Img and ForInpaint

ForImg2Img and ForInpaint are aliases for common usages of ByImage.

Sort out the confusion of strength and keep_until

Keep_until is replaced by bg_strength. The definitions are
* strength  -- strength applied to all layers
* bg_strength  -- strength applied only to the background layer

For image-to-image, bg_strength is typically set to 1.0.
For inpaint, bg_strength is typicaly set to 0.0.

Use explicit random seed when seed isn't specified

By this change, you can retrospectively get the random seed used in the previous generation from GetRandSeed().

Extended support for masks & refactoring

New support for masks
* ComboOf  -- allow applying arbitrary functions to list of masks to produce a combined mask
* ScaledMask  -- special case of `ComboOf` in the form of `ax + b`

misc fixes and additional features

The major changes in this commit are
- ByBothOf class  -- enable merging two initializers
- adjust parameter -- hack to mitigate Anything v3.0's VAE problem. See https://twitter.com/tomo161382/status/1601962971085041664
- scaler mask  -- allow a scaler value for mask instead of an image
- OpenImage function  -- a utility function to open an image from a path
- allow image path  -- allow a path string as an image argument for Layer, ByImage, and ByBothOf
- deterministic image encoder  -- an argument to make image encoding deterministic
- move num_steps and size to main function  -- num_steps and size are no longer an argument of the initializer

[Sample code]
prompts = {
    "prompt": "blue sky and mountain, near a big tree, animal on a hill",
    "negative": "",
    "cat": "white cat",
    "dog": "black dog",
}

def Generate():
  return pipe(
      num_steps=30,
      prompts = prompts,
      initialize=Randomly(),
      size=image_size,
      prompt_name="prompt",
      negative_prompt_name="negative",
      cfg_scale=7.5,
      layers=[
          Layer(
              mask="mask_right.png",
              prompt_name="cat",
          ),
          Layer(
              mask="mask_left.png",
              prompt_name="dog",
          ),
      ],
  )

Add LayeredDiffusionPipeline

LayeredDiffusionPipeline is a new custom pipeline rewritten from scratch.
It introduces layers to synthesize images generated by different prompts in parallel.

Sample images are available from https://twitter.com/tomo161382/status/1601400763141754880

Sample code:
prompts = {
    "prompt": "blue sky and mountain, near a big tree, animal on a hill",
    "negative": "",
    "cat": "white cat",
    "dog": "black dog",
}

def Generate():
  return pipe(
      prompts = prompts,
      initialize=Randomly(
          num_steps=30,
          size=image_size,
      ),
      prompt_name="prompt",
      negative_prompt_name="negative",
      cfg_scale=7.5,
      layers=[
          Layer(
              mask=OpenImage("mask_right.png"),
              prompt_name="cat",
          ),
          Layer(
              mask=OpenImage("mask_left.png"),
              prompt_name="dog",
          ),
      ],
  )

ability to save latent/img pairs, for training an approx decoder
provide a way to center denoising outputs on their means
multi-keyframe spherical latent walk, with a cubic-eased interpolation schedule
ensure we are at least as unmasked as our interpolation target

latent walk working. simplified the special treatment given to masking of '' prompts (now applies regardless of whether it's an uncond).
fix max context segments for WD 1.3, remove unused CFG var

defrag memory after denoising, so that we have enough contiguous memory to VAE decode large batches

disable attention mask when xformers is enabled
when a sample depends on a preceding sample's having been generated (e.g. to use it as feedback): flush anything prior to us in current batch.
delete now-unused vestiges of previous attempt

make denoiser stateful, to avoid computing `cond_in = cat([uncond, cond])` repeatedly (~462kB Tensor copy)
better idiom for upcasting just attention instead of everything
more semantic choice of model invocation concerns. add SD 2.1 (images black though).
fix "sampling in a different precision than the Unet"

demonstrate FP32 sampling of a FP16 UNet. not a big difference, not guaranteed nicer-looking, but technically more correct (and maybe it'll improve yield when doing seed searches in FP16, without the full perf cost of FP32). add WD1.4 VAE
stable diffusion v2 working on-CPU via k-diffusion. just noise on MPS.
add logging of train and test images to tensorboard
sample from my favourite timesteps only
add @isamu-isozaki's multi-token TI training support, plus some type hints and changes to work on latest diffusers. untested.
copy TI trainer to our repo so it can be changed here instead of maintaining a diffusers branch
factor out construction of embedder from tokenizer & text encoder, because ti_train has a need to share the embedder-maker code
give JPSD an extra sigma during which to draw torii. otherwise the yield is super low.

check in params for JPSD/WD exploration. did find that letting the Unets take turns worked better than mixing their results. good in some ways (runs faster if you run fewer Unets) but bad since it would be nice for both Unets to be involved in the whole schedule. could mean that the mixing approach isn't perfect.
sdxl stability->diffusers checkpoint conversion from kohya
